          "title": "The God who is not man — holiness as the ground of mercy",
          "body": "Verse 9 supplies the theological resolution: 'I will not execute My fierce anger; I will not destroy Ephraim again. For I am God and not man, the Holy One in your midst, and I will not come in wrath.' The expected sequence would be: God is holy → God will judge. Hosea inverts it: God is holy → God will not destroy. His holiness is the ground of His mercy, not the obstacle to it. This is theologically explosive. Human beings, when provoked to the degree that Israel has provoked God, retaliate to the full extent of their power. God does not — not because He lacks the power, but because His nature is categorically different from human nature. He is *el* (God), not *ish* (man). His responses are not governed by wounded pride or righteous human indignation but by a nature that holds justice and compassion in a unity that no human moral framework can replicate. The phrase 'the Holy One in your midst' (*qadosh beqirbeka*) is especially striking — the Most Holy is not distant from the people who have betrayed Him. He is in their midst, and His holiness in their midst is mercy, not only threat. Douglas Stuart (Word Biblical Commentary on Hosea) notes that this is the most concentrated expression in the book of Hosea's fundamental theology: God's character transcends the expectations of any human analogy."
